    correctAnswer: "E",
    explanation: `Cephalexin is empirically the preferred antibiotic to treat urinary tract infections (UTIs) in pregnancy. Nitrofurantoin and amoxicillin-clavulanate are second and third-line medications, respectively. Patients allergic to penicillin who manifest a rash can still be safely treated with cephalexin. If the penicillin allergy presented as anaphylaxis, cephalosporins would not be recommended, and the patient should be treated with nitrofurantoin. (Option A) Amoxycillin (without clavulanate) is only recommended if the organism is susceptible. Most UIT-causing organisms are resistant to amoxicillin. (Option B) Macrolides, e.g. clarithromycin, are not recommended for the treatment of UTI. (Option C) Aminoglycosides are category D and should not be used during pregnancy unless there is severe gram-negative sepsis. (Option D) Tetracyclines are contraindicated in pregnancy due to their potential teratogenic effects. NOTE—Asymptomatic bacteriuria (>10⁵ colony count in urine culture of an asymptomatic woman) during pregnancy should also be treated with a one-week course of antibiotics. The urine culture should be repeated 48 hours after treatment to confirm if the infection has resolved.`,
