    explanation: `The clinical manifestation is characteristic of urinary tract infection (UTI). Infectious cystitis is more likely in the absence of fever and flank pain. During pregnancy, the following antibiotics are considered safe for the treatment of UTI: First line: Cephalexin (category A) 500mg orally, 6-hourly for 10 days. Second line: Nitrofurantoin (category A) 50mg orally, 6-hourly for 10 days. Third line: Amoxycillin + clavulanate (category B1) 500+125mg orally, 12-hourly for 10 days. The above drugs are used for the treatment of asymptomatic bacteriuria of pregnancy as well. (Option B) Trimethoprim is an antagonist of folate, and there might be an increased potential risk of neural tube defects. Manufacturers advise that this drug be avoided during pregnancy. This drug, however, is the first-line therapy for UTI in non-pregnant women and adult men. (Option C) Tetracyclines, such as doxycycline and tetracycline, are contraindicated during pregnancy due to their risk of teratogenicity. (Option D) Nitrofurantoin is inferior to cephalexin for the treatment of UTIs during pregnancy. Moreover, it should be avoided in the near term due to the risk of neonatal hemolysis. It also should be avoided in those with renal impairment because the drug has renal excretion. (Option E) Ciprofloxacin is a fluoroquinolone. Although fluoroquinolones are categorised as B1 and are almost safe for use during pregnancy, they should not be considered first-line medications because they are the only orally active drugs available for infections due to Pseudomonas aeruginosa and other resistant bacteria to conventional antibiotics.`,
