    id: "inf-amedex-0023",
    topic: "Infectious Disease",
    subtopic: "Recurrent Urinary Tract Infection - Antibiotic Selection",
    stem: `Melanie, 45 years old, comes to your practice complaining of recurrent dysuria and increased frequency of urination. This is her fourth episode this year, and she has undergone previous antibiotic treatment with apparent resolution between episodes. She has hypertension, diabetes, and chronic kidney disease and takes amlodipine, insulin glargine, and insulin glulisine. She has never undergone any surgeries. Her recent glomerular filtration rate is 31 mL/min/1.73m2. She denies having vaginal discharge but engages in regular coitus with her husband. Lab tests show: Hgb 125 (Normal: 115-165 grams/L), Hct 0.51 (Normal: 37-47%), WBC 11.21 (Normal: 4-11 x 10⁹/L), Neutrophils 77 (Normal: 2.0-7.5 x 10⁹/L), Lymphocytes 18 (Normal: 1.5-4.0 x 10⁹/L), Eosinophils 0.01 (Normal: 0.04-0.4 x 10⁹/L), Platelet count 180 (157-371 billion/L). Chlamydia urine and high vaginal swabs: Negative. Gonorrhea urine and high vaginal swabs: Negative. Urine gram stain: Gram-negative rods. Urine culture and sensitivity: Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole – resistant, Azithromycin - sensitive, Cephalexin – sensitive, Nitrofurantoin – sensitive, Norfloxacin – sensitive, Meropenem - sensitive. Which of the following is the antibiotic of choice for this patient?`,
