    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Cephalexin is the drug of choice for this patient because it is safe to use even in patients with renal impairment. No renal adjustment is necessary for a creatinine clearance (CrCl) of 30 mL/minute or above. Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (option A) is incorrect because this patient has already developed antibiotic resistance. Nitrofurantoin (option B) is contraindicated in those with an eGFR of <45 mL/min/1.73m2 because it is renally excreted. Norfloxacin (option D) may treat acute UTIs unresponsive to other antibiotics but is not recommended as prophylaxis for patients with recurrent UTIs. Azithromycin (option E) is not currently recommended as a treatment for urinary tract infections but is considered if the patient has a concurrent chlamydia or gonorrhea infection. The patient tested negative for her STI workup. Doxycycline would be the preferred treatment if the patient had tested positive for Chlamydia as well. Non-antibiotic prophylactic measures are recommended including vaginal estrogen for postmenopausal women, postcoital voiding when intercourse is identified as a known trigger, methenamine hippurate 1g twice daily, and OM-89 E. coli oral vaccine.`,
