    explanation: `The scenario describes a patient with suspected bacterial pharyngitis who develops a rash after being started on amoxicillin. This is a common clinical situation where infectious mononucleosis (IM) is misdiagnosed as bacterial pharyngitis and the patient is started on antibiotics. IM is caused by Epstein-Barr virus and can mimic streptococcal tonsillitis with sore throat, fever, and exudate. The primary rash of IM is non-specific, pinkish and maculopapular (similar to rubella), occurs in only about 5% of cases, is usually blanching and non-pruritic. The secondary rash is most often precipitated by penicillins (especially ampicillin or amoxycillin), is non-blanching and itchy, and develops 5-9 days after antibiotics are started. About 90-100% of patients prescribed ampicillin or amoxycillin will be affected. The rash of this patient is most likely an allergic reaction to the antibiotic. The exact mechanism is not fully understood; some authors believe it is not a genuine allergic reaction because most patients will not be sensitive to the implicated antibiotic after IM resolves. Some theories suggest the rash is caused by both decreased immune system tolerance and enhanced immune response to the implicated drug during the infection.`,
