    explanation: `Higher human papilloma virus (HPV) infection rates have been reported in pregnant women. If condyloma develops, rapid growth can be observed. Contributing factors include immune system suppression during pregnancy and hormonal changes. Small asymptomatic lesions do not require treatment as most of them resolve after delivery. Large lesions can be treated with cryotherapy or keratolytics such as trichloroacetic acid (TCA) or bichloroacetic acid (BCA) as the preferred methods during pregnancy. Recurrences should be treated with same methods if complete response had occurred. Topical agents like interferon, podophyllin, podophyllotoxin, imiquimod and 5-fluorouracil are contraindicated throughout pregnancy except imiquimod (category B1), though safety evidence is limited and requires full patient informed consent. Genital warts are diagnosed clinically; biopsy for PCR is only required if diagnosis is not certain. Blood culture is not indicated to diagnose HPV infection. Observation until after delivery would be correct if lesions were small and asymptomatic. Excision is used if the wart is very large and macerated only, often after the first trimester.`,
