    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `The painful lump in the eyelid with normal vision and eye movements, in the presence of normal systemic health and afebrile status, is consistent with either stye (external hordeolum) or meibomian abscess (internal hordeolum). Both conditions are often managed conservatively with application of heat and massage to allow drainage of infected contents. This is followed by oral di/flucloxacillin in meibomian abscess and sometimes by topical chloramphenicol in stye. Incision and curettage under local anaesthesia (option E) is the treatment of last resort or when the abscess is large. Intravenous antibiotics (option B) are used if peri-orbital or orbital cellulitis is suspected. CT scan of the orbit (option A) is an important part of management if orbital cellulitis is suspected.`,
