    explanation: `Of all the studies shown in the forest plot, only two do not cross the lines of "no effect"; hence, only two are statistically significant. A forest plot is a graphical representation commonly used in meta-analyses and systematic reviews to display the results of multiple studies on the same topic. It helps visualise the effect sizes, confidence intervals, and overall outcomes of various studies clearly and concisely. Horizontal lines extend from each square to represent the confidence interval (CI) for the effect size. A wider line indicates a less precise estimate. Suppose the confidence interval crosses the line of no effect (usually represented as a vertical line at 1 for risk or odds ratios). In that case, it suggests that the study's result is not statistically significant—generally, the bigger the boxes, the larger the study population. The overall pooled effect size, which combines the results of all studies, is often shown at the bottom of the plot. A diamond shape typically indicates this. The centre of the diamond represents the pooled effect size, and the width represents the confidence interval. The vertical line of no effect helps assess quickly whether the results are statistically significant. For example, in the case of odds ratios, a line at 1 indicates no difference between groups. In standardised mean differences (SMD) cases, the line could be at 0, representing a line of no effect.`,
