    id: "ph-amedex-0067",
    topic: "Public Health",
    subtopic: "Fitness to drive and medical ethics",
    stem: `Steven is a 67-year-old patient who presented a year and a half ago for a health review before renewing his driver's license. Your examination revealed 6/24 vision for both eyes; therefore, you advised that he should not drive anymore and encouraged him to self-report to licensing authorities and be referred for assessment by an ophthalmologist. Today, he presented again and asked if you could change your mind and give him a letter so that he could drive. You examine him again and realise he still has poor eyesight and is unfit to drive. When you tell him so, he becomes irritated and says that he saw another doctor who gave him a letter last year and has been driving since then. Why do you not just give him a similar letter as well? Which of the following is the most appropriate action now that you know him driving despite his unfitness to drive?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Call the police.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Call the doctor who issued the letter and ask him why he has done so.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Report the patient to the relevant Road and Traffic department.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Ask him to drive only if there is someone else in the car to supervise him.` },
      { label: "E", text: `It is not your duty to report him to anyone. Tell him again that he is unfit to drive and must submit his license to authorities.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "E",
    explanation: `According to Australian Road Safety (Austroads), a person is not fit to hold a driver's license if: For private drivers, the better eye's corrected visual acuity (with glasses or contact lenses) is less than 6/12. For commercial drivers, the corrected visual acuity is less than 6/18 for the worse eye and less than 6/9 for the better eye. This patient's visual acuity is 6/24 in both eyes, which is less than the minimum standard. Therefore, he is not fit to drive and should be referred to an ophthalmologist or optometrist for a clinical assessment regarding the driving task. Assessing fitness to drive is one of the most challenging situations in medical practice. On one side are the patient's important issues, such as independence and probably financial matters, especially for commercial vehicle drivers, and on the other side is the health and safety of the public. A medical practitioner should be able to balance their duty to the patient and the duty to act in the public's interest. When a patient is likely to pose a risk to the health and well-being of others, it should become apparent to the patient that driving under their medical condition is dangerous for them and the public. Many patients will likely choose not to drive when the condition is explained empathetically and reasonably. The patient should also become aware of their civil responsibility to self-report the medical condition to the driver licensing authorities. This discussion and advice should be documented in the patient's notes. However, it is important to note that the relationship between a patient and the treating doctor is confidential; therefore, doctors will not typically communicate directly with the Driver Licensing Authority and will provide the patient with advice about the ability to drive safely as well as a letter or report to take to the authority. The doctor must not report the patient to the police (option A) or driving licensing authority (option C) directly. They must refuse to sign the 'fitness to drive' form and encourage the patient to self-report himself. In terms of the duty to the public, if a doctor believes that a patient is not heeding advice to cease driving, they may report directly to the Driver Licensing Authority; however, this reporting is not mandatory except in South Australia (SA) and the Northern Territory (NT). In this case, Steven should be made aware of all the risks involved and his responsibility to self-report and not drive. If you form a belief that he will not follow the instructions and is likely to place the public at risk, you may choose to report or must report to authorities, depending on the state you are practising in. (Option C) It is not a doctor's responsibility to investigate other doctors' decisions and actions. Calling the doctor who allegedly has given the patient a certificate of fitness to drive is beyond a doctor's practice limits. (Option D) The presence of a supervisor does not make an unfit person fit to drive.`,
