    explanation: `Cerebrovascular events (e.g. stroke, TIA) make the patient unfit to drive non-commercial vehicles for at least four weeks. Once there is no residual deficit, and the risk of recurrence is minimised by appropriate measures such as prophylactic anticoagulation, the patient should be assessed by an occupational therapist (or any other relevant consultants such as an ophthalmologist, neurologist, etc., depending on the residual defects) for evaluation of fitness to drive. A wide range of practical assessments are available, including off-road, on-road and driving simulator assessments, each with strengths and limitations. Assessments may be conducted by occupational therapists trained in driver assessment or others approved by the driver licensing authority. Processes for initiating and conducting driver assessments vary between the states and territories, and the choice of the evaluation depends on resource availability, logistics, cost and individual requirements. The assessments may also be initiated by the examining health professional, other referrers (e.g., police, self, family), or the driver licensing authority. In this case, improvement should be assessed by an occupational therapist and ophthalmologist. Any further process regarding private or commercial driving depends on expert opinions from these disciplines.`,
