    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Assessing fitness to drive is one of the most challenging situations in medical practice. On one side are the patient's important issues, such as independence and, in this case, the financial problems Daniel will face if he is prevented from driving as a commercial driver, and on the other side, the health and safety of the public. A medical practitioner should be able to balance their duty to the patient and the duty to act in the public's interest. In case a patient is likely to pose a risk to the health and well-being of others, the following measures should be taken: STEP 1 - Most importantly, it should become apparent to the patient that driving under their medical condition is dangerous both for him/her and the public. Many patients will likely choose not to drive when the condition is explained empathetically and reasonably. STEP 2 - The patient should become aware of their civil responsibility to self-report their medical condition to the driver licensing authorities. This discussion and advice should be documented in the patient's notes. STEP 3 - Reporting to the licensing authorities if the patient: is unable to understand the impact of their condition; OR is unable to take notice of the health professional's recommendations due to cognitive impairment; OR continues driving despite appropriate advice and is likely to endanger the public. Daniel has a provisional diagnosis of sleep apnea (or other sleep disorders) that has resulted in daytime sleepiness. Driving while drowsy or sleepy poses a significant risk to his or others' health. This should be explained to him as the first step in management. He should also be asked to self-report to driving licensing authorities (option B). If you discover Daniel keeps driving despite the advice, you can breach confidentiality and personally inform the authorities (option C). (Option D) Asking patients to surrender their driver's licenses is not a task for doctors. Doctors are not in a position, legally or morally, to make such a request. (Option E) Weight reduction will benefit Daniel not only for sleep apnea but also in general health and should be advised; however, it is long-term management with future results and is not likely to resolve his daytime sleepiness in the short term. NOTE – The take-home message of this question is that talking to the patient and convincing them to stop driving voluntarily and follow your recommendations is always the most important first step in cases of unfitness to drive.`,
